<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="stopping-treatment-opening">
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In Part 2, we modeled regular dosing with the recurrence
      </p>

      <me>H_{n+1}=aH_n+D.</me>

      <p>
        Now suppose treatment is interrupted. After the final dose, there are no
        additional doses, so the concentration only decays.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>H_0</m> be the concentration immediately after the final dose.
        After one dosing interval, the concentration becomes
      </p>

      <me>H_1=aH_0.</me>

      <p>
        Write formulas for <m>H_2,H_3,H_4</m>. Then write a general formula for
        <m>H_n</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose that before treatment is interrupted, the concentration is close
        to the steady state
      </p>

      <me>H^\ast=\frac{D}{1-a}.</me>

      <p>
        Under regular dosing, the model predicts that the concentration stays
        near <m>H^\ast</m>. After interruption, the model becomes
      </p>

      <me>H_n=a^nH^\ast.</me>

      <p>
        Use this formula to complete the table below.
      </p>

      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell><m>n</m></cell>
          <cell>Regular dosing</cell>
          <cell>After interruption</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>0</m></cell>
          <cell><m>H^\ast</m></cell>
          <cell><m>H^\ast</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>1</m></cell>
          <cell><m>H^\ast</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>2</m></cell>
          <cell><m>H^\ast</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>3</m></cell>
          <cell><m>H^\ast</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>4</m></cell>
          <cell><m>H^\ast</m></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose the concentration needs to stay above a threshold <m>L</m>.
        After interruption, the concentration is modeled by
      </p>

      <me>H_n=a^nH^\ast.</me>

      <p>
        We want to know when the concentration falls below <m>L</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Starting from
      </p>

      <me>a^nH^\ast \lt L,</me>

      <p>
        solve for <m>n</m>. Your answer should involve logarithms.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>a=0.545</m>, corresponding approximately to a half-life of
        <m>8</m> days and a dosing interval of <m>7</m> days. Suppose also that
        a threshold is <m>25\%</m> of the steady-state concentration:
      </p>

      <me>L=0.25H^\ast.</me>

      <p>
        Find the first integer <m>n</m> such that
      </p>

      <me>a^nH^\ast \lt 0.25H^\ast.</me>

      <p>
        How many weeks does this represent?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The number <m>L</m> in the previous exercises is a simplified threshold.
        In real clinical contexts, thresholds may depend on the medication,
        route of administration, lab values, individual physiology, and treatment
        goals.
      </p>

      <p>
        Why is it useful to study threshold models anyway? What can a simplified
        model show clearly, even when it does not capture every biological
        detail?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Some policies or administrative decisions interrupt access to medication
        by delaying refills, blocking appointments, changing insurance coverage,
        or restricting care.
      </p>

      <p>
        Using the model from this part, explain why a short administrative delay
        may have consequences that depend on timing. In your answer, refer to at
        least two of the following:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>half-life,</li>
        <li>dosing interval,</li>
        <li>steady state,</li>
        <li>threshold crossing,</li>
        <li>time since last dose.</li>
      </ul>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>